We want now to analyse the situation at a particular area. So we are going to create an index with the specific areas we are interested in.

index <- us_states$STATE_NAME == "Texas" | us_states$STATE_NAME == "New Mexico" |
  us_states$STATE_NAME == "Oklahoma" | us_states$STATE_NAME == "Arkansas"

AoI_sf <- us_states_sf[index,]

# plot it
tm_shape(AoI_sf) + tm_borders(col = "black") + tm_layout(frame = F) + 
  # add the torn points
  tm_shape(torn_sf) + tm_dots(col = "#FB6A4A", size = 0.2, shape = 1, alpha = 0.5)

torn_clip_sf <- torn_sf[index,]

# replot it using the clipped torn points
# plot it
tm_shape(AoI_sf) + tm_borders(col = "black") + tm_layout(frame = F) + 
  # add the torn points
  tm_shape(torn_clip_sf) + tm_dots(col = "#FB6A4A", size = 0.2, shape = 1, alpha = 0.5)

As it is shown above, such operations might not produce the ideal results, since the spatial subsetting is based simply on their actual spatial extents and not on their spatial relationship. sf package offers the st_intersection function, which can be used for such operations.

AoI_torn_sf <- st_intersection(AoI_sf, torn_sf)
## although coordinates are longitude/latitude, st_intersection assumes that they are planar
## Warning: attribute variables are assumed to be spatially constant throughout all
## geometries
# plot it 
tm_shape(AoI_sf) + tm_borders(col = "black") + 
  # add the respective torn points
  tm_shape(AoI_torn_sf) + tm_dots(col = "#FB6A4A", size = 0.2, shape = 1, alpha = 0.5) + tm_layout(frame = F)

So, ultimately, as we can see above, the st_intersection function creates a datasets where the point dataset is precisely clipped based on the area of interest.
